assemblage.p:
\begin{align*}
\log_b b \amp = 1 \text{ because } b^1 = b \\
\log_b 1 \amp = 0  \text{ because } b^0 = 1 \\
\log_b{bx} \amp = x \text{ because } b^x = b^x
\end{align*}

statement.p:
	Rewrite each equation in logarithmic form.



8^{-1/3} = \dfrac{1}{2}


5^x = 46

example.p:
		Approximate the following logarithms to 2 decimal places.



\log{6.5}


\log{256}

subsection.p:
We can check the approximations found in  with our conversion equations. Remember that a logarithm is an exponent, and in this example the base is 10. We find that
\begin{align*}
\amp\amp 10^{0.81} \amp\approx 6.45654229 \\
\text{and} \amp\amp 10^{2.41} \amp\approx 257.0395783
\end{align*}
so our approximations are reasonable, although you can see that rounding a logarithm to 2 decimal places does lose some accuracy.

solution.p:
First, we isolate the power of 10: We subtract 95 from both sides of the equation and divide by -15 to obtain
\begin{align*}
-57 \amp = -15 \cdot 10^{0.4x} \amp\amp \text{Divide by }-15. \\
3.8 \amp = 10^{0.4x}
\end{align*}
Next, we convert the equation to logarithmic form as
\log_{10}{3.8} = 0.4x
Solving for x yields
\frac{\log_{10}{3.8}}{0.4}= x
We can evaluate this expression on the calculator by entering

statement.p:




		\log {(3.8}







		.5795835966


But if we want to evaluate \dfrac{\log{3.8}}{0.4}, we must enclose 3.8 in parentheses, as shown in . If we omit the parenthesis after 3.8, the calculator will interpret the expression as \log{\left(\dfrac{3.8}{0.4}\right)}, which is not the expression we wanted.
